1. The "Please install elephant" Error

Walker 1.0 completely split its code in half. Walker is now just the "dumb" visual frontend, and it relies on a new background engine called Elephant to do the actual heavy lifting (finding apps, searching files, doing math).

Because you are on an Arch-based system, you can easily install the engine and all of its official search providers:
Bash

paru -S elephant-all-bin

(Using the -bin package saves you from having to compile a bunch of Go code).

Once it installs, start the background service:
Bash

systemctl --user enable --now elephant.service

2. The "Failed to detect any valid GPUs" Error

This is a classic VMware graphics issue. Walker is built using the modern GTK4 toolkit, which defaults to using the Vulkan rendering engine. VMware's virtual graphics driver does not support Vulkan properly, causing the VK_ERROR_INITIALIZATION_FAILED crash.

To fix this, we just need to tell Walker to use standard OpenGL instead of Vulkan.

Since you have a beautifully modular Niri configuration, here is the cleanest way to set it up:
A. Run Walker as a Background Service

To make Walker open instantly when you press your shortcut, it should run silently in the background from the moment you log in. Open your autostart file:
Bash

nano ~/.config/niri/cfg/autostart.kdl


add these lines

spawn-at-startup "elephant"
spawn-at-startup "sh" "-c" "GSK_RENDERER=gl walker --gapplication-service" 


