Ah, the classic AUR packaging quirk! It looks like the elephant-all-bin package either didn't bundle the official .service file, or your systemd daemon just hasn't refreshed to see it yet.

But honestly? Since you are using a custom Wayland compositor like Niri, relying on systemctl to manage your background apps can sometimes be more of a headache than it's worth. We can bypass systemd completely and just let Niri handle both engines directly!

Here is how to get it running perfectly without the missing service file:
1. Add Elephant to Niri's Autostart

Since we already opened your autostart file for Walker, let's just add Elephant right above it.

Open your file:
Bash

nano ~/.config/niri/cfg/autostart.kdl

Make sure the bottom of your file has both of these lines. Niri will start the data engine first, and then start the Walker UI service right after it:
Code snippet

spawn-at-startup "elephant"
spawn-at-startup "sh" "-c" "GSK_RENDERER=gl walker --gapplication-service"

Save (Ctrl+O, Enter) and Exit (Ctrl+X).

2. Start them right now (Without rebooting)

Since Niri only runs autostart commands when you first log in, we just need to manually kickstart them for this current session so you can test it immediately.

Run these two commands in your terminal:
Bash

elephant &

(Press Enter again to get your terminal prompt back, then run:)
Bash

GSK_RENDERER=gl walker --gapplication-service &

3. Test it out!

Press your Super + Space shortcut. Walker should pop up instantly in the center of your screen, perfectly rendered in OpenGL, with the Elephant engine humming in the background. Try typing =50*1.08 to see if the calculator module instantly kicks in!

