The edit you just made to your autostart.kdl file actually did make it permanent! Every time you turn on your computer and log into Niri, those two lines will automatically launch both Elephant and Walker in the background.

However, relying on your window manager to start a heavy background data engine like Elephant isn't always the most bulletproof method. If the Elephant engine crashes in the background, Niri won't restart it for you.

If you want to do this the "proper" Arch Linux way and create that missing systemd service yourself (so it runs perfectly in the background and auto-restarts if it ever crashes), it is incredibly easy to do.

Here is how to make a permanent, robust system service for Elephant:
1. Create the Systemd Folder

First, make sure the folder for your personal user services exists:
Bash

mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user/

2. Create the Service File

Open a new file for the Elephant service using nano:
Bash

nano ~/.config/systemd/user/elephant.service

3. Paste the Configuration

Paste this exact block of text into the file. This tells your system what Elephant is, how to start it, and to automatically restart it if it ever fails:
Ini, TOML

[Unit]
Description=Elephant Data Engine for Walker
After=graphical-session.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/bin/elephant
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=3

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target

Save (Ctrl+O, Enter) and Exit (Ctrl+X).
4. Enable the Service

Now, tell systemd to reload its files so it notices the new one you just made, and then enable it permanently:
Bash

systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now elephant.service


Awesome! Since Elephant is built to be blazing fast, it doesn't just blindly scan your entire hard drive by default. It usually limits itself to your Home folder, but you can heavily customize exactly what it looks at—and more importantly, what it ignores (like massive hidden .cache folders or game libraries).

Here is how to dial in exactly where it searches:
1. Open the Elephant Files Config

Elephant separates its configuration into different files based on the module. The one that controls your hard drive search is files.toml.

Open your terminal and run:
Bash

mkdir -p ~/.config/elephant
nano ~/.config/elephant/files.toml

2. Tell it Where to Look

If the file is empty (or doesn't exist yet), that is completely normal. You can paste this exact block in to set up your custom search parameters.

Adjust the folders inside the brackets to match your actual workflow:
Ini, TOML

[files]
# Directories you actively want Walker to search
paths = [
    "~/Documents",
    "~/Downloads",
    "~/Pictures",
    "~/Projects"
]

# Directories you want it to completely ignore (speeds up search!)
ignored_paths = [
    "~/.cache",
    "~/.local",
    "~/.cargo",
    "~/Games"
]

# Do you want to find hidden files (files starting with a dot)?
show_hidden = false

(Pro-tip: Keeping show_hidden set to false and ignoring your .cache folder will make your file searches basically instantaneous).
3. Save and Restart the Engine

    Save the file (Ctrl+O, Enter) and Exit (Ctrl+X).

    Because Elephant runs as a background service now, it won't read this new config file until you restart it. Since we set it up as a systemd service earlier, just run:
    Bash

    systemctl --user restart elephant.service

Now, hit Super + Space and type find  followed by the name of a file you know is in your Documents or Downloads folder. It should instantly pop up!

