Ah, I know exactly what is happening! This is a classic Linux Wayland quirk, and the fix depends on exactly what you saw on your screen right before the browser opened.

There are two different things that cause this. Let's squash whichever one is happening to you:
Scenario A: It did a Google search for the words "find..."

What's happening: You typed find [filename], and Walker didn't show you a list of local files. Instead, it just defaulted to doing a web search for exactly what you typed.
Why: Walker isn't communicating with the Elephant background service properly, so it doesn't know what the find keyword means and falls back to its web search module.
The Fix: Make sure the Elephant service is actually running in your current session. Run this in your terminal:
Bash

systemctl --user restart elephant.service

Wait about 5 seconds, then try searching again. If Elephant is running properly, typing find  should instantly change the Walker UI to show local files.
Scenario B: It found the file, but opened it in the browser anyway

What's happening: Walker successfully displayed your file in the search results, but when you pressed Enter, it opened in Firefox/Brave instead of your file manager or image viewer.
Why: This is notorious on Linux. It's called "MIME Hijacking." Web browsers aggressively tell the underlying system, "Hey, I can open PDFs, images, and even folders!" Because Niri is a minimal window manager, it doesn't have a heavy settings daemon fighting back against the browser, so the browser steals the default associations.
The Fix:
We need to use the xdg-mime command to force the system to hand those files back to your actual apps.

Open your terminal and run these commands to set your file manager (assuming you are using the standard CachyOS/GNOME file manager, Nautilus) as the absolute default for opening folders and unknown files:
Bash

xdg-mime default org.gnome.Nautilus.desktop inode/directory
xdg-mime default org.gnome.Nautilus.desktop application/x-directory

If it's opening images in the browser, you can route them back to your image viewer (like Loupe or whatever is installed):
Bash

xdg-mime default org.gnome.Loupe.desktop image/png
xdg-mime default org.gnome.Loupe.desktop image/jpeg

(Note: If you use a different file manager like Thunar or Dolphin, just replace org.gnome.Nautilus.desktop with thunar.desktop or org.kde.dolphin.desktop).

